§ Why ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ What is the multiplicative inverse in the reals? ⦉
⦉

§ Result ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ We can show the following.
    † ⦊
      ‖ The account will appear in future editions. ⦉
    ⦉⦉
⦉

<statement type='proposition'>
  ‖ The multiplicative inverse of $R ∈ 𝗥$, $R ≠ 0_{𝗥}$,
    𝍫 ⦊
      ‣ ‖ if $0_{𝗤} ∈ R$, then
          ◇ ⦊
            ‖ S = \Set*{q ∈ 𝗤}{q ≤ 0_{𝗤}} \union \Set*{r^{-1}}{∃s
              < r, (r ∉ R)} ⦉
          ⦉
          is a multiplicative inverse of $R$. ⦉⦉

      ‣ if $0_{𝗤} ∉ R$, then case (1) applies to $-R$. Let $S$
        be the multiplicative inverse of $-R$. Then the additive
        inverse of $S$, i.e., $-S$ is a multiplicative inverse of
        $R$. ⦉
    ⦉⦉
</statement>

§§ Notation ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ We denote the multiplicative inverse of $r ∈ 𝗥$ by $∈v{r}$. ⦉

  ‖ We denote $q · (\inv{r})$ by $q/r$. ⦉
⦉

§§ Division ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ We call the operation $(a, b) ↦ a/b$ ❬real division❭. ⦉

  ‖ We call the product of $a$ and the multiplicative inverse
    of $b$ the ❬(real) quotient❭ of $a$ and $b$. ⦉
⦉

